# data-models-relationships

Key Data Models and Relationships:

1. Youth Profile Model
Importance Score: 95
- Core profile entity with specialized behavioral health attributes
- Relationships:
  * One-to-many with DailyPerformanceNotes 
  * One-to-many with BehaviorIncidents
  * One-to-many with AcademicRecords
  * One-to-many with BehavioralAssessment
  * Many-to-many with TreatmentGoals
  * One-to-one with MedicalProfile
- Domain-specific fields:
  * Treatment level (1-6)
  * Current restrictions
  * Behavioral point totals
  * Active interventions
  * Guardian relationships

2. Daily Performance Notes Schema
Importance Score: 90
- Structured behavioral tracking across 4 domains
- Relationships:
  * Many-to-one with Youth
  * One-to-many with BehaviorIncidents
  * One-to-many with StaffNotes
- Behavioral metrics:
  * Peer interaction rating (1-4)
  * Adult interaction rating (1-4)
  * Investment level (1-4)
  * Authority response (1-4)

3. StaffNotes Schema
- Staff-authored annotations attached to a DailyPerformanceNote or BehavioralAssessment record
- Fields:
  * id (string, unique): auto-generated UUID
  * parentType (string): "DailyPerformanceNote" or "BehavioralAssessment" — identifies which entity this note annotates
  * parentId (string): foreign key referencing the parent record id
  * youthId (string): foreign key referencing the Youth record
  * authorId (string): foreign key referencing the Staff/User record
  * authorRole (string): role of the author at time of writing (e.g., "direct_care", "case_manager", "clinical_supervisor")
  * content (string, required, max 2000 characters): free-text annotation body
  * createdAt (ISO 8601 timestamp): set at creation, immutable
  * updatedAt (ISO 8601 timestamp): updated on every edit
  * isAmendment (boolean): true if this note corrects a prior entry; default false
  * amendedNoteId (string, nullable): id of the note being corrected, populated when isAmendment is true
- Relationships:
  * Many-to-one with DailyPerformanceNotes (via parentId when parentType = "DailyPerformanceNote")
  * Many-to-one with BehavioralAssessment (via parentId when parentType = "BehavioralAssessment")
  * Many-to-one with Youth (via youthId)
  * Many-to-one with Staff/User (via authorId)

4. Medical Profile Schema
Importance Score: 85
- Healthcare-specific youth data model
- Relationships:
  * One-to-one with Youth
  * One-to-many with Medications
  * One-to-many with MedicalAlerts
- Clinical tracking:
  * Current medications
  * Dosage schedules
  * Allergies/restrictions
  * Medical conditions
  * Treatment authorizations

5. TreatmentGoals Model
Importance Score: 80
- Treatment planning and goal tracking
- Relationships:
  * Many-to-many with Youth
  * One-to-many with Interventions
  * Many-to-many with BehavioralMetrics
- Focus categories:
  * Behavioral objectives
  * Social skill development
  * Academic goals
  * Family integration
  * Life skills mastery

6. Behavioral Assessment Schema
Importance Score: 75
- Point-based behavior tracking system
- Relationships:
  * Many-to-one with Youth
  * One-to-many with BehaviorIncidents
  * One-to-many with StaffNotes
- Assessment metrics:
  * Daily point totals
  * Rolling averages
  * Level progression data
  * Restriction tracking

Core Entity Relationships:
- Youth as central entity
- Treatment goals linked to behavioral metrics
- Medical profiles with medication tracking
- Daily notes connected to incidents
- Assessment data tied to interventions
- StaffNotes attached to both DailyPerformanceNotes and BehavioralAssessment records (see StaffNotes Schema above for full field definitions and relationship cardinality)

